The paper deals with network formation games, which are typically studied in the game theory (cs.GT) and networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. The use of an adversary model to randomly delete links adds a layer of complexity to the analysis, which could also place the paper in the social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-category. The paper also involves analyzing equilibria and the price of anarchy, which are common topics in the algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) and information theory (cs.IT) sub-categories.
